Question 4- Analyze the tip_amount to identify any outliers. You can assume the outliers are 3 standard deviations from the mean. Comment on the outliers that were detected; after which, remove the outlier tip_amount from the data.

#Calculate mean, sd and z score
mean_df <- mean(tripdata_df$tip_amount)
sd_df <- sd (tripdata_df$tip_amount)
z_df <- abs((mean_df- tripdata_df$tip_amount)/ sd_df)
#Outliers are 3 z- scores away from either side of the mean
outliers <- tripdata_df[which(z_df >3),]
summary(outliers$tip_amount)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  -10.56    8.25    9.47   11.61   11.76  641.20
#The below code removes outliers
no.o <- tripdata_df[-which(z_df >3),]
dim (no.o)
## [1] 394884     21

#Comment : There are 3748 outliers with minimum value of $-10.56, maximum value of $641.20 and mean of $11.61. It is surprising to see a negative tip value and such a huge maximum value too. The original mean of the entire tip amount is 0.9 which is 10 times The last code (no.o) shows that outliers are removed. Original set had 398632 obs, removing 3748 outliers, the new set has 394884 observations.

Question 6- State at least two methods/techniques that can be used to handle missing data. Which approach would you recommend, is suitable, to handle missing values in this dataset? Answer- Techniques to handle missing data are: 1) Omit them from the data set 2) Replace it with something. If is in an intrinsic missing value i.e. it is not present in the data frame, we can make it extrinsic by replacing with NA. for this the complete() as well as setting values_drop_na = TRUE in pivot_longer() can be done 3) We can also fill the missing values as per the last non-missing value using fill(). These can be used in cases when a data source is used for data entry.

For our data set, we should identify the missing data first using is.na(). Since the ehail_fee column is entirely missing it can be dropped, in all other places we can use na.rm()= TRUE to not consider missing values. In a bar graph, missing values are seen seperately and in a histogram, they are removed so the data integrity is maintained.
